</taxonomicName>
was also recorded from the 
<collectingRegion id="9522F868BD6EFFFFFC41FB4BE91DFB08" box="[1134,1353,1186,1212]" country="Russia" name="Khabarovsk" pageId="1" pageNumber="174">Khabarovsk region</collectingRegion>
, (Botchi Fm., 
<collectingCountry id="2FF1761ABD6EFFFFFB4BFB2CEFE4FB54" box="[868,944,1221,1248]" name="Russia" pageId="1" pageNumber="174">Russia</collectingCountry>
) (
<bibRefCitation id="33774B7BBD6EFFFFFBE8FB2CE8D5FB6B" author="Rasnitsyn, A. P." box="[967,1153,1221,1247]" pageId="1" pageNumber="174" pagination="56 - 70" refId="ref5012" refString="Rasnitsyn, A. P. (1983) Fossil Hymenoptera of the superfamily Pamphilioidea. Paleontological Journal, 17, 56 - 70." type="journal article" year="1983">Rasnitsyn, 1983</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="5759368ABD6EFFFFFB70FB01EF23FA07" blockId="1.[810,1452,516,2092]" pageId="1" pageNumber="174">
<emphasis id="6592EA98BD6EFFFFFB70FB01E84CFAB6" bold="true" box="[863,1048,1256,1282]" pageId="1" pageNumber="174">Redescriptions.</emphasis>
<materialsCitation id="E78E3CD7BD6EFFFFFC32FB01E966FAD8" ID-GBIF-Occurrence="3763876303" accessionNumber="UCM 19165" collectionCode="UCM" pageId="1" pageNumber="174" specimenCount="1" typeStatus="holotype">
These fossil wasps show rather well preserved body and wing structures, but, unfortunately, the legs are missing in all the specimens. The 
<typeStatus id="885D8828BD6EFFFFFD00FAC6E9C5FAFD" box="[1327,1425,1327,1353]" pageId="1" pageNumber="174">holotype</typeStatus>
is less well preserved than 
<accessionNumber id="48B5AB69BD6EFFFFFC6BFABBE887FAD9" box="[1092,1235,1362,1389]" httpUri="http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/protein/UCM19165" pageId="1" pageNumber="174">
<collectionCode id="31F7AE4FBD6EFFFFFC6BFABBE8D0FAD8" box="[1092,1156,1362,1388]" country="USA" httpUri="http://biocol.org/urn:lsid:biocol.org:col:34854" lsid="urn:lsid:biocol.org:col:34854" name="University of Colorado Museum of Natural History" pageId="1" pageNumber="174" type="University or college">UCM</collectionCode>
19165
</accessionNumber>
(
<figureCitation id="CFDD2A0FBD6EFFFFFCCBFABBE97DFAD8" box="[1252,1321,1362,1388]" captionStart="FIGURE 2" captionStartId="2.[136,235,2001,2025]" captionTargetBox="[138,1449,1336,1977]" captionTargetId="figure-264@2.[138,1449,1336,1977]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="FIGURE 2. Tapholyda caplani (Cockerell, 1933), UCM 19165. A, Rock piece with the specimen. B, Photograph, arrowheads indicate fusion traces. Scale bars = 10 mm (A), 5 mm (B)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6530329" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6530329/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="174">Fig. 2</figureCitation>
)
</materialsCitation>
<materialsCitation id="E78E3CD7BD6EFFFFFD15FABBEF9FFA3B" ID-GBIF-Occurrence="3763876302" accessionNumber="UCM 35546" collectionCode="UCM" pageId="1" pageNumber="174" specimenCount="1" typeStatus="holotype">
and 
<accessionNumber id="48B5AB69BD6EFFFFFD43FABBEF24FA24" httpUri="http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/protein/UCM35546" pageId="1" pageNumber="174">
<collectionCode id="31F7AE4FBD6EFFFFFD43FABBE9F8FAD8" box="[1388,1452,1362,1388]" country="USA" httpUri="http://biocol.org/urn:lsid:biocol.org:col:34854" lsid="urn:lsid:biocol.org:col:34854" name="University of Colorado Museum of Natural History" pageId="1" pageNumber="174" type="University or college">UCM</collectionCode>
35546
</accessionNumber>
(
<figureCitation id="CFDD2A0FBD6EFFFFFB51FA9CEF95FA3B" box="[894,961,1397,1423]" captionStart="FIGURE 3" captionStartId="3.[136,235,1765,1789]" captionTargetBox="[145,1443,189,1742]" captionTargetId="figure-87@3.[145,1443,189,1742]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="FIGURE 3. Tapholyda caplani (Cockerell, 1933), UCM 33546. A, Rock piece with the specimen. B, Photograph. C, Detailed photograph of left forewing. D, Detailed photograph of right forewing. E, Interpretative line drawing of forewing venation with vein and cell names labeled. Scale bars = 5 mm (A, B), 1 mm (C–E)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6530331" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6530331/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="174">Fig. 3</figureCitation>
)
</materialsCitation>
. 
<materialsCitation id="E78E3CD7BD6EFFFFFBFAFA9FEF20FA07" ID-GBIF-Occurrence="3763876301" accessionNumber="UCM 35546" collectionCode="UCM" pageId="1" pageNumber="174" specimenCount="1" typeStatus="holotype">
We mainly base the redescription on 
<accessionNumber id="48B5AB69BD6EFFFFFD43FA9CEF20FA07" httpUri="http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/protein/UCM35546" pageId="1" pageNumber="174">
<collectionCode id="31F7AE4FBD6EFFFFFD43FA9CE9F8FA3B" box="[1388,1452,1397,1423]" country="USA" httpUri="http://biocol.org/urn:lsid:biocol.org:col:34854" lsid="urn:lsid:biocol.org:col:34854" name="University of Colorado Museum of Natural History" pageId="1" pageNumber="174" type="University or college">UCM</collectionCode>
35546
</accessionNumber>
</materialsCitation>
.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="5759368ABD6EFFFFFB70FA55E8ABF8A7" blockId="1.[810,1452,516,2092]" pageId="1" pageNumber="174">
Head nearly rounded, about 1.1 times as wide as long; fore margin of clypeus curved and protruding medially; mouthparts poorly visible; scape and pedicel broader than first flagellomere, first flagellomere 1.0 mm long, longer than second + third ones, broader than other flagellomeres, with fusion traces of five–six inflexibly connected basal flagellomeres as indicated by faint lines and very small incisions on the inner margin when observed under alcohol (visible in 
<typeStatus id="885D8828BD6EFFFFFC86F93CE95FF95B" box="[1193,1291,1749,1775]" pageId="1" pageNumber="174">holotype</typeStatus>
specimen, see 
<figureCitation id="CFDD2A0FBD6EFFFFFB05F910EF39F8A7" box="[810,877,1785,1811]" captionStart="FIGURE 2" captionStartId="2.[136,235,2001,2025]" captionTargetBox="[138,1449,1336,1977]" captionTargetId="figure-264@2.[138,1449,1336,1977]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="FIGURE 2. Tapholyda caplani (Cockerell, 1933), UCM 19165. A, Rock piece with the specimen. B, Photograph, arrowheads indicate fusion traces. Scale bars = 10 mm (A), 5 mm (B)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6530329" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6530329/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="174">Fig. 2</figureCitation>
, arrowheads), 15–16 flagellomeres.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="5759368ABD6EFFFFFB70F8F5E86CF877" blockId="1.[810,1452,516,2092]" pageId="1" pageNumber="174">Thorax.Pronotum narrow; mesoprescutum triangular with a medial carina; mesoscutum triangular-shaped; notauli distinct; mesoscutellum rather large, triangular; mesoscutellar appendage distinct; cenchri rounded; metascutellum rounded.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="5759368ABD6EFFFFFB70F825E8F6F798" blockId="1.[810,1452,516,2092]" pageId="1" pageNumber="174">Abdomen slightly wider than mesonotum; terga with laterotergite separation apparent on dorsal surface; genitalia insufficiently preserved.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="5759368ABD6DFFFCF892FF77EEC4FDD1" blockId="2.[136,778,158,614]" pageId="2" pageNumber="175">Forewing hyaline, with pterostigma lanceolate elongate, well sclerotized and darkened; Sc2 subvertical, well basad 1-Rs, shorter than 1-Rs; R distinctly curved before Rs base and distinctly bent at Rs base; vein 1-Rs long, more than twice as long as half of 1-M, at maximum nearly equal to 1-M in length; M+Cu distinctly curved without trace of angle; no ap-Cu vein; cell 1mcu shorter than length of pterostigma; cell 2r much wider than cell 2rm; crossvein 3r-m clearly longer than 6-Rs; crossvein 1cu-a close to mid-length of cell 1mcu, between 0.7 and 0.8 depending of the specimen; cell 1R distinctly longer compared to its width (ratio length/width = 2).</paragraph>
<paragraph id="5759368ABD6DFFFCFB70FF77EFF8FF6B" blockId="2.[810,1452,158,616]" pageId="2" pageNumber="175">Hind wings poorly preserved in all specimens, hardly discernible.</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
